{"cursor":"9950","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nIn mathematics and physics, the 'right-hand rule' is a common mnemonic for\nunderstanding notation conventions for vectors in 3 dimensions. It was invented\nfor use in electromagnetism by British physicist John Ambrose Fleming in the\nlate 19th century. {{cite book\n  | last = Fleming first = John Ambrose authorlink = coauthors = title = Magnets\n  | and Electric Currents, 2nd Edition publisher = E.& F. N. Spon year = 1902\n  | location = London pages = 173â174 url =\n  | http://books.google.com/books?id=ASUYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA173 doi = id = isbn =\n  | }}\n\nWhen choosing three vectors that must be at right angles to each other, there\nare two distinct solutions, so when expressing this idea in mathematics, one\nmust remove the ambiguity of which solution is meant.\n\nThere are variations on the mnemonic depending on context, but all variations\nare related to the one idea of choosing a convention.\n","linknr":223,"url":"Right-hand_rule","recorded":1362560160,"links":50,"instances":["mathematics","mathematics","mathematics","physics","geometry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Electromagnetism","Mechanics","Orientation","Vectors","Rules of thumb","Mnemonics"],"headings":["The right-handed screw","Right-handed and Left-handed coordinates","Direction associated with an ordered pair of directions","Direction associated with a rotation","Applications","Left-hand rule","Symmetry","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e2/Cartesian_coordinate_system_handedness.svg/220px-Cartesian_coordinate_system_handedness.svg.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/79/Rechte-hand-regel.jpg/220px-Rechte-hand-regel.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf9/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/8/7/8/87880e7b1c1c042da0a25baf511d113c.png","//uploa